<H1><U7:P></U7:P>William E. McCarthy</H1>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><![if =
!supportEmptyParas]><![endif]>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" =
align=3Dcenter><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;</SPAN></SPAN></I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">Department of=20
Accounting<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"> and =
Information=20
Systems<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" align=3Dcenter><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">Michigan State =
University<U7:P></U7:P>, East=20
Lansing, MI 48824, USA<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" align=3Dcenter><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><A=20
href=3D"mailto:mccarth4@msu.edu">mccarth4@msu.edu</A>;=20
517/432-2913<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></I> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify; mso-outline-level: =
1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>ABSTRACT:&nbsp;</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">Conceptual models =
of=20
enterprises can be used for both business process modeling and the =
actual design=20
of computerized information systems.The Resource-Event-Agent (REA) =
model, a=20
domain-specific framework for determining the information architecture =
of=20
accounting and enterprise information systems, has primarily been used =
for=20
design purposes.In this paper we explore the use of REA for business =
process=20
modeling.At first, we discuss how REA primitives are used to describe =
the=20
value-added transformation of resources throughout the enterprise. Next, =
we=20
analyze some difficult specification problems that relate to business =
process=20
modeling in general and to REA engineering solutions to these problems =
in=20
particular.We conclude the paper with the specification of a three-layer =

architecture that summarizes the REA approach to business process =
modeling: (i)=20
enterprise-level specification, (ii) REA-based process descriptions, and =
(iii)=20
task-level or workflow specifications.The architecture shows that =
workflow=20
descriptions can be related to the specification of the enterprise value =
chain=20
through the medium of REA information structures.<U7:P></U7:P> =
<BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -1.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><B><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>KEY=20
WORDS:</B><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbs=
p;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">Accounting =
information=20
systems, business process modeling, enterprise value chain, REA model. =
workflow=20
modeling.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 12pt"><![if =
!supportEmptyParas]><![endif]>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></P><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U=
7:P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"mso-outline-level: 1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">1.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp; =
</SPAN>INTRODUCTION<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B>=20
<BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The =
discipline of=20
enterprise information system engineering has dramatically changed in =
recent=20
years.Two major innovations of significant import are briefly discussed=20
below.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>a.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><I>Advances in information technology -- such as client-server=20
architectures, object technology and a variety of Internet technologies =
such as=20
XML -- are dramatically changing the way enterprise systems are =
designed,=20
implemented, andoperated.</I><U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>The =
use of=20
object-oriented technology has resulted in a decrease of the semantic =
gap=20
between the analysis, design and implementation phases of information =
systems=20
(Jacobson 1992, Walden and Nerson 1995). As a result, conceptually =
designed=20
business models can be fully carried into implementation, and the links =
between=20
different enterprises are much tighter. XML (extensible markup language) =

technologies promise to couple different enterprise systems together =
much more=20
closely than they are historically accustomed to (Bradley 2000, Hoque=20
2000).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>b.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><I>Conceptual design methods have been assigned a dual role =96 =
the=20
understanding of the business as well as the actual design of the =
enterprise=20
information system</I> (Jacobson et al. 1995, Taylor 1995, Eriksson and =
Penker=20
2000).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>Historically,=20
conceptual models have been used primarily to capture information =
requirements=20
and to translate these requirements smoothly into a variety of database =
and=20
file-oriented platforms (such as network, hierarchical and relational=20
systems).According to Batini et al. =93<I>Conceptual design starts from =
the=20
specification of requirements and results in the conceptual schema of a=20
[particular] database.=94</I> (1992, p.6).&nbsp;More recently, Gale and =
Eldred=20
(1996, p. 121) describe the new purpose of conceptual modeling as: =
=93<I>to=20
construct a model of any kind of domain using a set of theoretical =
modeling=20
constructs that capture the way the world really is.=94</I>In a business =

environment, this world consists (among other things) of business =
processes and=20
business rules.The practice of <B>B</B>usiness <B>P</B>rocess=20
<B>R</B>eengineering or BPR (Hammer and Champy, 1993) requires accurate =
modeling=20
and documentation techniques for business realities, and conceptual =
models turn=20
out to be an excellent tool for these purposes.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> =
<BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>These =
advances in=20
technology and specification methods have also dramatically changed the=20
applicability of a particular conceptual method -- the REA=20
(<B>R</B>esource-<B>E</B>vent-<B>A</B>gent) model (McCarthy 1982, Geerts =
and=20
McCarthy, 2000a).The REA model was introduced by McCarthy in 1982 as a=20
domain-specific theory for the <B>design</B> of accounting information =
systems,=20
and its use has gradually been expanded to the modeling of economic =
phenomena in=20
general (Geerts and McCarthy, 1994; 2000a).A main characteristic of REA =
is that=20
it heavily relies on first-order accounting principles. The use of REA =
for the=20
actual design of information systems has been widely discussed in the =
literature=20
(see for example: McCarthy (1982), Gal and McCarthy (1986), Hollander et =
al.=20
(2000), Romney and Steinbart (2000), Hall (2001), and Geerts and =
McCarthy=20
(2000a, 2000b, 2001)).Geerts and McCarthy (2000b) describe how =
knowledge-based=20
technology enables transformation of REA from a mere design methodology =
into an=20
<B>operational framework </B>for information =
systems.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>In this =
paper, we focus=20
on the concurrent use of REA for the design of an enterprise=92s =
conceptual=20
information architecture and for business process modeling.We start with =
a brief=20
discussion of Porter=92s enterprise value chain concept, and we relate =
that=20
framework to business process engineering in general and to the REA =
model in=20
particular.To illustrate the meaning of REA concepts, we next introduce =
a simple=20
business example that is used throughout this paper: the=20
<B>R</B>ent-<B>A</B>-<B>C</B>razy-<B>C</B>ar (RACC) Business. We =
illustrate an=20
REA object template explosion for one of RACC=92s main business =
processes=20
(maintenance), and we construct a simple REA-based value chain for =
RACC.The=20
paper then analyzes some difficult specification problems that relate to =

business process modeling in general and to REA engineering solutions to =
these=20
problems in particular.With these specification problems discussed, the =
paper=20
returns to its central BPM focus and shows how low-level, =
function-oriented=20
information processing tasks can be related to high-level models of =
value-added=20
behavior through the medium of REA information structures.We do this =
with=20
examples drawn from the renting process of RACC. We end with some =
conclusions=20
and further research directions.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"mso-outline-level: 1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>2.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp; </SPAN>ENTERPRISE VALUE CHAINS WITH=20
RESOURCE-EVENT-AGENT&nbsp;<SPAN style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN>COMPONENTS<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Michael =
Porter=92s (1985)=20
<I>Value Chain</I> concept =93was developed as a systematic method for =
examining=20
all the activities a firm provides and how they interact=94 (Callon, =
1996, p.=20
47).As Callon (1996) notes, Porter=92s value chain idea in its original=20
incarnation was used primarily as a source for analyzing competitive=20
advantage.It did not include the notion of providing customer value as =
the=20
ultimate objective, nor was it ever intended to be used as a framework =
for the=20
information architecture of an enterprise.In actual practice however, =
Porter=92s=20
product and service flows can be arranged as a series of input-output =
processes=20
with resource flows between them (Geerts and McCarthy, 1994; 1999), =
which have=20
the ultimate objective of customer value:<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; =

<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 27pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify; tab-stops: -.5in; =
mso-line-height-alt: 1.0pt; mso-hyphenate: none"><SPAN=20
lang=3DEN-GB=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; LETTER-SPACING: -0.15pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB"><U7:P></U7:P>A=20
fundamental notion in value chain analysis is that a product gains value =
(and=20
costs) as it passes through the vertical stream of production within the =
firm=20
(design, production, marketing, delivery, service).When created value =
exceeds=20
cost, a profit is generated.This notion of value creation is derived =
from the=20
economics of demand.Products are viewed as bundles of attributes =
(Lancaster,=20
1975) which can be configured in multiple ways to appeal to segments of=20
consumers having diverse demand functions (Hergert and Morris, 1989,=20
p.183).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><SPAN lang=3DEN-GB =
style=3D"mso-ansi-language: EN-GB">=20
</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 12pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify; tab-stops: -.5in; =
mso-line-height-alt: 1.0pt; mso-hyphenate: none"><![if =
!supportEmptyParas]><![endif]>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></P><U7:P></U7:P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">A value chain at =
its highest=20
level of abstraction for a typical manufacturing company (Callon, 1996, =
p. 48)=20
might include product and service flow through: (1) research and =
development,=20
(2) engineering, (3) production and manufacturing, (4) marketing, (5) =
sales and=20
distribution, and (6) service.Each step in this chain can be considered =
a=20
<I>process</I> as Hammer and Champy (1993, p. 53) define it: =93A =
collection of=20
activities that takes one or more kinds of input and creates an output =
that is=20
of value to the customer.=94<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>In an =
economic sense, a=20
<I>process</I> is a production function wherein the entrepreneur or =
manager of=20
an enterprise exchanges some input resource(s) for some output =
resource(s) of=20
greater value to the customer.For example, in the third process shown in =
the=20
paragraph above (production and manufacturing), the inputs would be =
labor,=20
machines, and raw material which are converted into goods that have more =
value=20
to the customers than the sum of the values of the inputs. In the fourth =
process=20
(marketing), the inputs could be cash and manufactured goods which are =
then=20
converted to advertised final goods (something of more value to the=20
customer).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify; mso-outline-level: =
1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>2.1.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Decomposition of an =

enterprise value chain<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; =
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The =
manufacturing=20
company specified above would have six processes in its simplest and =
most=20
abstract form.In a realistic information system engineering setting, =
most of=20
these would need to be decomposed further before actual process =
engineering=20
would start.This is illustrated in the process hierarchy of figure 1 and =

explained below.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1025 height=3D600 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;m-fig1.jpg" width=3D450 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.2in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>At =
the top of=20
figure 1, an <I>enterprise value chain</I> is portrayed as a series of =
connected=20
inflow-outflow processes. Each business process is adding value by =
converting=20
resources into a more valuable (to customers) resource.The new resource =
is then=20
used as input by another business process. The <I>business process=20
decomposition</I> layer, in the middle of figure 1, illustrates further=20
decomposition of one of the business processes in the enterprise value =
chain.=20
The decomposition consists of two =93leaf=94 nodes on either side of a =
middle=20
process that is decomposed yet further.Let us suppose that the<I> =
production and=20
manufacturing</I> process, which is part of the enterprise value chain, =
can be=20
further decomposed into three sub-processes --<I> set-up, assembly</I>, =
and=20
<I>inspection</I> -- with the first and third of these being leaf =
processes=20
(i.e., not needing further decomposition).Further, we may suppose that =
the=20
sub-process<I> assembly</I> can be decomposed into three more parts:<I>=20
combining, welding</I>, and <I>painting</I>.This gives us an example for =
the=20
three-level decomposition shown.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Each =
<B>process </B>in=20
an enterprise value chain (at any level of abstraction or decomposition) =
has at=20
least two composite<B> economic</B> <B>events</B>: a decrement event =
that=20
consumes the inputted resource and an increment event that acquires the=20
outputted resource.For example, a revenue process has a sale event =
(consumption=20
of inventory input) and a cash receipt event (acquisition of cash =
output).As we=20
shall see in the event template description below, the REA model =
provides a=20
representation pattern for these events and for other objects within a=20
process.At a later point in the paper, we will discuss situations where =
these=20
increment/decrement events might be modeled at a conceptual level below =
the=20
lowest process decomposition.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>In any =
decomposition of=20
enterprise business processes, a heuristic is needed for stopping the=20
decomposition.The one we adopt here is adapted from Hollander et al. =
(2000) --=20
<I>conceptual modelers decompose from the enterprise-level value chain =
down=20
until they reach the lowest level at which decision-makers need =
information: (1)=20
to plan and design the operation and sequencing of activities of the =
future, and=20
(2) to monitor the operation of activities of the present, and (3) to =
evaluate=20
the operation ofactivities of the past.</I> Beyond this point, decision=20
usefulness wanes and implementation technology details become =
overwhelming.In=20
figure 1 we use this heuristic to stop further decomposition of the =
middle=20
bottom process in layer 2. Any further specifications of a bottom level =
process=20
are accomplished via task descriptions. Task-level or workflow =
specifications=20
are portrayed as the bottom layer in figure 1, and specification of =
workflow=20
occurrences is a point we return to later in the =
paper.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify; mso-outline-level: =
1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>2.2.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The REA object=20
template<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent><SPAN style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><U7:P></U7:P>We defined a business process above as an =
entrepreneur=20
exchange or transformation where input is changed into output with the =
express=20
objective of providing customer value.Each process has at least one =
input=20
consumption event and one output acquisition event. McCarthy=92s (1982) =
REA model=20
is a semantic model for an economic exchange that pairs two mirror-image =
event=20
object patterns, one of them a template for a give (a consumption event) =
and the=20
other a take (an acquisition event).Geerts and McCarthy (2000a) further =
refine=20
the semantic description of an economic exchange and we use their =
representation=20
in the rest of this paper. An REA object template for a single process =
is=20
illustrated in figure 2 and explained below. </P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1026 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig2.gif" width=3D660 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Two of =
REA=92s primitives=20
are <I>Economic Event</I> and <I>Economic Resource</I>.Economic Event is =
the=20
central dynamic primitive of McCarthy=92s domain theory and is described =
by Yu=20
(1976, p.256) as =93<I>a class of phenomena which reflect changes in =
scarce means=20
resulting from production, exchange, consumption, and distribution=20
[processes].</I>=94Economic Events are critical information elements of =
an=20
enterprise information system that describe the inflow (consumption) and =
outflow=20
(acquisition) of Economic Resources. Economic Resource is the central =
static=20
primitive of the domain theory, and it describes the stock of resources =
kept at=20
a certain point in time. Obviously, this stock is affected by Economic =
Events,=20
and this relationship is reflected in the <I>Stock-Flow</I> primitive =
(figure=20
2).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Another REA =
primitive=20
is the concept of <I>Exchange</I> or <I>Give-Take</I> relationship that =
is=20
titled <I>Duality</I> in figure 2.Fisher (1906, p.149) describes an =
exchange (or=20
transfer) as follows: =93<I>transfers usually occur in pairs, and =
involve two=20
objects transferred in opposite directions between two owners.This =
double=20
transfer, we have called exchange.=94</I><U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify; tab-stops: 13.5pt =
.5in 1.0in 1.5in 2.0in 2.5in 3.0in 3.5in 4.0in 4.5in 5.0in 5.5in 6.0in =
6.5in; mso-hyphenate: none"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The =
remaining REA=20
primitives are used to model the <I>Inside Agents</I> and <I>the Outside =

Agents</I> involved in the Economic Events.Inside Agents are usually =
employees=20
accountable for the Economic Events, while Outside Agents are the =
external=20
parties involved in the exchange. The relationships connecting the =
Economic=20
Event with the inside and outside Agents are named <I>Participation</I>=20
relationships.<SPAN class=3DMsoFootnoteReference><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-special-character: footnote"><![if =
!supportFootnotes]>[1]<![endif]></SPAN><U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></SPAN><A=20
title=3D"" style=3D"mso-footnote-id: ftn1"=20
href=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-maintext.htm#_ftn1"=20
name=3D_ftnref1></A></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>If we combine =
the value=20
chain model of figure 1 with the process object pattern of figure 2, we =
derive=20
the extended REA model described by Geerts and McCarthy (1994; 1999).In=20
actuality, this extended model has some other declarative and procedural =

primitives (such as the concept of resource-event-agent typification =
plus the=20
concepts of commitments and claims), but a discussion of these is beyond =
the=20
scope of this paper which focuses on process engineering.Interested =
readers may=20
consult Geerts and McCarthy (2000a).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>A full =
economic data=20
model for an enterprise may be derived by exploding each of the leaf =
node=20
processes of its decomposed value chain into its REA components.We will=20
demonstrate this procedure in the context of a specific example in the =
next=20
section of the paper.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><BR><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"mso-outline-level: 1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">2.3.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The =
Rent-A-Crazy-Car (RACC)=20
example</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN><U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Figure 3 =
shows the=20
result of applying the REA object template to one of the business =
processes=20
(maintenance) of our business example:=20
<B>R</B>ent-<B>A</B>-<B>C</B>razy-<B>C</B>ar (RACC). We will explain =
RACC=92s=20
business first.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1027 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig3.gif" width=3D660 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>R</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt">ent-<B>A</B>-<B>C</B>razy-<B>C</B>ar=20
(RACC) is a small company that buys crazy cars (like a pink Cadillac, a =
madras=20
microbus, a yellow Beetle convertible, a polka-dot hearse, etc.) and =
rents them=20
out.RACC has a small number of highly specialized employees (agents) who =
select=20
cars and then rent them. Craziness (or uniqueness) is probably the =
attribute=20
that customers value most about RACC=92s products.RACC cars are often =
rented for=20
weddings, political campaigns, big formal dances, etc.Another attribute=20
customers highly value is that the car they rent works on that =
=93special=94 day.To=20
realize this objective, the cars are sent out to various automobile =
service=20
centers at periodic intervals by rental agents for different types of=20
maintenance.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 11.7pt; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">To rent a car, a =
customer=20
sends a request to RACC.Based on the customer=92s request, RACC=92s =
employees=20
(rental agents) check if the requested type of car is available.When a =
car is=20
available, an appropriate insurance policy is selected and a contract is =

prepared.The rental contract is sent to the customer.The customer must =
pay the=20
rental fee first before he or she can pick up the car.Upon receipt of =
the=20
payment (check), the rental agent approves the contract and sends a copy =
to the=20
lot-attendant. The customer goes with his contract to the lot-attendant. =
The=20
lot-attendant picks up the car and updates the information in the car=20
database.The customer also returns the car to the lot-attendant who =
updates the=20
product database to close the =
transaction.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt"><U7:P></U7:P><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Figure 3 =
illustrates=20
that we have to give up resources (cash) to acquire a maintained car. =
The REA=20
object template defines =93Maintenance=94 as an Economic Event resulting =
in an=20
inflow of Car (or Car Service) from the Service Center =
(take).Maintenance adds=20
value to the Car resource as the following attribute: =93the car should =
work well=20
on the customer=92s special day.=94The REA object template in figure 3 =
also shows=20
=93Cash Disbursement=94 as an Economic Event resulting in an outflow of =
the Economic=20
Resource =93Cash.=94<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Figure 4 =
shows a more=20
detailed REA-based description for the =93Maintenance=94 Economic =
Event.We have=20
added cardinalities using the Batini et al. (1992) =
notation.Cardinalities are=20
used to express domain-specific rules: that is, business policies =
applied by the=20
enterprise. The cardinalities for the Car-Maintenance (C-M) Stock-Flow=20
relationship express the following business =
policies:&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN>=20
<BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2><U7:P></U7:P>[1,1] -- for each maintenance =

transaction (Economic Event) exactly one car (Economic Resource) is =
recorded;=20
</P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2>[0,n] -- not all cars (Economic Resource) =
have=20
necessarily been involved in a maintenance transaction (Economic Event) =
but the=20
same car can be involved in many maintenance transactions. <BR>&nbsp; =
</P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1028 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig4.gif" width=3D660 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The other =
cardinalities=20
in figure 4 express business policies applied by RACC as well.For =
example, the=20
same Inside Agent can be responsible for many maintenance transactions. =
Case in=20
point, Thelma is responsible for a set of maintenance transactions:=20
{001,002,003}.RACC often relies on the same Service Center (i.e. the =
same=20
Outside Agent can be involved in many different transactions).For =
example, East=20
Lansing Midas has done the maintenance transactions {004,005}.When =
combined with=20
REA-structures, cardinalities are a powerful tool for the modeling of =
accounting=20
phenomena. Readers may consult McCarthy (1982),Hollander et al. (2000), =
Hall=20
(2001) and Romney and Steinbart (2000) for an in-depth discussion of the =
use of=20
semantic constructs such as cardinalities for modeling accounting=20
phenomena.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Figure 5 =
shows a=20
partial data model (omitting duality cash transactions) for RACC=92s =
significant=20
business activities.The diagram in figure 5 integrates REA-templates for =
three=20
Economic Events:acquisition of cars [Purchase], maintenance of cars=20
[Maintenance] and the actual renting of cars [Rental Contract].The =
integrated=20
model precisely describes the acquisition (Purchase, Maintenance) of car =

services and the use of these car services (Rental Contract).The =
additional=20
specification of inside agents and outside agents results in an =
information=20
architecture that supports responsibility and control procedures, =
planning=20
procedures, and evaluation procedures.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1029 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig5.gif" width=3D660 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>In figure 6, =
we=20
reinstate the cash duality transactions for the processes mentioned in =
the=20
paragraph above to derive a value chain.The REA logic here models how =
resources=20
are acquired and consumed in a purposeful manner throughout the =
enterprise:=20
=93<I>Taken as a whole, duality relationships are the glue that binds a =
firm=92s=20
separate economic events together into rational economic processes, =
while=20
stock-flow relationships weave these processes together into an =
<B>enterprise=20
value chain=94</B></I> (Geerts and McCarthy 97a, p.98). In the next =
section of the=20
paper, we will focus on the use of this resource =
acquisition/-consumption=20
network for business process modeling and=20
reengineering.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><BR>&nbsp; =
<BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1030 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig6.gif" width=3D666 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>3.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp; </SPAN>AN REA APPROACH TO BUSINESS =
PROCESS=20
MODELING<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B><o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The main goal =
of=20
business process modeling and reengineering is to manage the integrated=20
organization instead of the stovepiped organization.Integrated process=20
management is possible only when the business processes are known and=20
understood, something that requires a cross-functional synthesis of =
economic=20
events and workflow tasks into business processes.There are methods =
available in=20
the literature for accomplishing this.For example, Harrington (1991) =
discusses a=20
set of graphical techniques to model business processes.Additionally, =
some=20
object-oriented tools such as Object Life Cycles (Shlaer and Mellor, =
1992) or=20
Use-Cases (Jacobson, 1992; Jacobson et al., 1995) are also =
appropriate.However,=20
as we have seen with our RACC examples, REA logic and organization also =
seems=20
well suited to this unification process, and we discuss its more =
detailed use as=20
such in the paragraphs that follow.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><BR><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify; mso-outline-level: =
1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">3.1<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>REA events =
and the need=20
for task-level specification<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; =
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>As we saw in =
figure 1,=20
business processes can be decomposed into subprocesses multiple times =
before an=20
enterprise modeler finds the level at which it is appropriate to explode =
the=20
process into a full set of matched REA patterns.For example, RACC=92s =
acquisition=20
process can be decomposed into vendor selection, order preparation, =
receiving=20
goods, and vendor payment. Yourdon et al. (1995, p. 137) warn analysts =
to be=20
=93<I>careful when partitioning a process along the time axis, that each =

subprocess has a reasonable scope from beginning to end.Consider whether =
it=20
delivers something of value to the customer.Otherwise there is a danger =
of=20
falling back into a function-oriented breakdown of processes =85=94 =
</I>Again, a=20
working heuristic that gives both an approximate start for object =
tracking and=20
an approximate finish to process decomposition is to stop at the level =
at which=20
decision makers need information to plan, design, monitor, and evaluate =
economic=20
activities.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>At the leaf =
level in a=20
process decomposition of a value chain, an REA template like figure 2=20
appears.However, a full-REA process model<SPAN =
class=3DMsoFootnoteReference><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-special-character: footnote"><![if =
!supportFootnotes]>[1]<![endif]></SPAN></SPAN>=20
is often more complex than this diagram illustrates because the full set =
of=20
resource inputs and outputs entails more detail.For example, the revenue =
process=20
at the bottom of figure 6 shows =93Car=94 (of various types) as input =
with =93Cash=94=20
and =93Used Car=94 as outputs, and it is certainly true that in an =
entrepreneurial=20
logic sense, these are the major process components.That is, we make =
money by=20
relinquishing the use of our cars for a period of time in turn for which =
we=20
receive cash from customers.However, it should also be obvious from the =
company=20
description given earlier that this process consumes other resources =
such as=20
employee labor.Thus a full-REA model of the revenue process ought to =
include a=20
=93Labor Consumption=94 event as well as the =93Rental Contract=94 and =
=93Cash Receipt=94=20
events.However, full-REA modeling as we describe it is often not =
technologically=20
attainable, nor is it often decision useful.It is for these cases that =
we=20
propose an additional level of REA decomposition which we call the =
<B><I>Task=20
Level</I></B>.We illustrate the need for these at the bottom of figure =
1, and we=20
describe the rationale for delineating tasks in the section that=20
follows.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <A title=3D"" =
style=3D"mso-footnote-id: ftn2"=20
href=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-maintext.htm#_ftn2"=20
name=3D_ftnref2></A></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><BR><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify; mso-outline-level: =
1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">3.2<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Criteria for=20
Differentiating Between Economic Events and =
Tasks<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B>=20
<BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>In theory, =
all=20
occurrences in time that consume resources are actually Economic Events =
in a=20
full-REA world.However, as mentioned above, we sometimes will find it =
convenient=20
to classify some occurrences as tasks. The criteria for differentiating =
between=20
an <I>Economic Event</I> and a <I>Task</I> are highly heuristic and=20
situation-specific in their application.However, the two critical =
factors in our=20
opinion are these: (1) whether or not an occurrence in time can be =
paired=20
logically and (somewhat) immediately with an acquisition (increment) =
event that=20
produces an identifiable and representable resource and (2) whether the =
specific=20
representation of that occurrence in time is at a level needed to plan, =
design,=20
monitor, and evaluate.The judgments needed to apply these criteria are =
explained=20
below with the assistance of the process illustration in figure=20
7.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1031 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig7.gif" width=3D666 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>A process in =
the=20
entrepreneurial logic sense is an exchange that brings the entrepreneur =
one step=20
closer to the goal of providing a full value portfolio to the final =
customer.In=20
this sense, business processes (as illustrated in figure 7) usually have =
a=20
defining major resource consumption-acquisition pairing.For example, =
this would=20
be <I>sale -- cash-receipt</I> in the revenue process and<I> =
cash-disbursement=20
-- purchase</I> in the materials acquisition process.Almost inevitably =
these=20
economic conversions will incur other costs as well that enable the=20
exchange.These additional items can be considered&nbsp;<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-bidi-font-style: italic">transaction</SPAN>costs in an =
exchange.For=20
example, the transaction costs for the acquisition and revenue processes =

mentioned above would include the employee labor use involved in the =
purchases,=20
sales, cash receipts, and cash disbursements.In addition to labor, =
processes=20
often entail costs for other resources.Good examples would be car or =
computer=20
use for a salesperson.We propose that many transaction costs be modeled =
as tasks=20
instead of as events with the result that their specification is done at =
the=20
documentation or workflow level as opposed to the data model=20
level.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Representing =
an=20
occurrence at the task level means rolling its data representation into =
one of=20
the two major events in the process.For example, the labor use involved =
in the=20
revenue process wouldn=92t be represented as a separate consumption =
event but as=20
an attribute of sale or of cash-receipt.As documentation of the workflow =
needed=20
to effect a sale, we could specify its tasks (such as telephone the =
customer,=20
write down the order, check credit, etc.).This is what we show at the =
bottom of=20
figure 1 in the task box.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Rolling the=20
representation of labor and enabling-resource consumption events into =
the major=20
give-take events of a process (that is, making them tasks instead of =
events)=20
makes sense when some of these conditions=20
apply:<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>1.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>notation of the task=92s =
completion=20
is clearly immaterial in an information-provision sense (that is, it =
isn=92t=20
needed for managerialplanning, designing, monitoring, or=20
evaluating);<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>2.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>the task completion =
process is=20
highly technology-dependent or technology-volatile (that is, both its =
need and=20
its substance can change with technology);&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN>=20
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>3.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>the task doesn=92t affect =
an=20
identifiable acquired resource (of value to the customer) whose =
representation=20
can be materialized until after the completion of all process tasks;=20
and&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 31.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>4.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>the set of tasks needed =
to=20
accomplish a consumption event is congruent (that is, its cardinality =
pattern is=20
(1,1) (1,1) ) with the major increment or decrement events of a=20
process.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyText2 style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN><U7:P></U7:P>In an REA=20
setting, using these heuristics is bound to prove difficult at the =
margin, but=20
we think their application will prove tremendously useful.Separation of=20
resource-consuming occurrences in time into the separate specification =
groups of=20
economic events and tasks will provide a sound basis for process=20
reengineering.Economic Events are fundamental parts of entrepreneur =
logic, and=20
they should be reengineered with great reluctance.Tasks on the other =
hand are=20
less intrinsic to the value-creation process of the firm.As such, they =
are=20
constant candidates for reevaluation and reengineering. </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><BR><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"mso-outline-level: 1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">3.3<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Event and =
Task=20
specification for RACC<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; =
<o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Following the =

discussion above, we can view the revenue process for RACC as a =
collection of=20
occurrences in time.Examples would be accept customer contact, assess =
customer=20
needs, check car file &amp; choose the car, assess insurance policy =
needs and=20
choose, prepare the contract, collect the money, etc.Each of these could =
be=20
typed as events and exploded as REA templates.However, if we apply the=20
heuristics above, some of them become specified as =93the set of tasks =
needed to=20
accomplish a rental contract and a cash receipt for that contract.=94As=20
illustrated in figure 8, many of them are now decomposed to the task =
level=20
(shown as a fishbone diagram at the bottom of the page).Actually, the =
bottom=20
part of figure 8 illustrates all of the cross-functional tasks needed to =

accomplish the Revenue Process of RACC.The REA object patterns are used =
only for=20
the major decrement-increment pairing of<I> rental contract --=20
cash-receipt</I>.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <BR>&nbsp; </P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1032 height=3D600 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig8.jpg" width=3D450 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 13.5pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify; tab-stops: =
4.5in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>Figure 9=20
illustrates the use of system flowcharts (Hall 2001; Romney and =
Steinbart 2000;=20
Hollander et al. 2000) to model the cross-functional tasks performed by =
RACC in=20
support of its revenue cycle.We assume that only two functional =
departments are=20
involved here: <B>Rental-Agent</B> and <B>Lot-Attendant</B>.System =
flowcharts=20
are very helpful in modeling workflow and in documenting communication =
between=20
functional departments.These flowcharts can also be used to speculate on =

reengineering possibilities.For example, RACC could decide to let =
customers=20
=93Check and Choose=94 the cars themselves by giving them Internet =
access to the Car=20
database.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><BR>&nbsp;=20
<o:p></o:p></SPAN></P>
<P><IMG id=3D_x0000_i1033 height=3D495 hspace=3D1=20
src=3D"http://www.msu.edu/user/mccarth4/G&amp;M-fig9.gif" width=3D666 =
vspace=3D1=20
border=3D0><BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>Figure 8 =
summarizes the=20
REA approach to Business Process Modeling. Although not illustrated in =
figure 8,=20
readers should realize that only some of the business processes will be =
further=20
decomposed and that only the leaf (bottom-level) business processes in =
the=20
hierarchy (see figure 1) will be exploded into REA=20
templates.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN><o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The REA =
approach can be=20
used for top-down analysis as well as bottom-up analysis.The =
=93enterprise level=94=20
diagram (top of figure 8) integrates the key business processes into a =
value=20
chain.In addition to the =93value-added=94 processes, the key resource =
inputs and=20
outputs are clearly specified.Furthermore, it is clearly specified to =
what=20
extent business processes rely on each other. Figure 8 in the middle =
shows an=20
REA explosion for a leaf process. The give-take relations describe =
precisely the=20
value-added transformations for the business process.The invariant=20
entrepreneurial logic of RACC is clearly delineated, and the portion of =
their=20
enterprise system clearly susceptible to reengineering review on a =
periodic=20
basis is also clear.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><BR><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"mso-outline-level: 1"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt">4.<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp; </SPAN>CONCLUSIONS AND FURTHER =
RESEARCH=20
DIRECTIONS<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN></B> <BR>&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P><SPAN =

style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>The REA =
accounting=20
model was introduced in 1982 as: =91<I>A Generalized Framework for =
Accounting=20
Systems in a Shared Data Environment=92</I> (McCarthy, 1982).A =
<I>first</I> major=20
objective of the REA framework was to replace functional-driven, =
isolated file=20
systems by an integrated information structure.Instead of building =
separate and=20
redundant applications for order processing, shipping, billing, etc., =
one=20
cross-functional enterprise-wide information structure was to be=20
specified.Database technology has historically enabled the =
implementation of=20
such an enterprise-wide information structure, and object technology =
with=20
components promises even better platforms for direct=20
implementation.&nbsp;<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: 1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN>A =
<I>second</I>=20
objective of the REA framework was the domain-specific structuring of =
the=20
enterprise-wide information architecture.Applying the REA template =
results in a=20
integrated network describing how resources are consumed through =
value-added=20
processes.This makes REA not only a valuable tool for the actual design =
of the=20
enterprise information system but also for business process modeling =
itself.In=20
this paper, we discussed the use of REA object templates to engineer =
business=20
processes and tasks. We summarize below some of the characteristics of =
this=20
approach.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3><U7:P></U7:P>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN>REA can be used for both business process modeling and the actual =
design=20
of the information system. <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN>REA supports the domain-specific structuring of the process =
descriptions,=20
resulting in precise, domain-specific, descriptions of the enterprise =
value=20
chain.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN>The multi-level REA structure allows business process analysis as =
well as=20
task analysis.That is, we can ask:does a business process add value and =
can we=20
reengineer the task structure for a certain business=20
process.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>This =
paper is=20
an attempt to use REA for the express purpose of business process =
modeling.Some=20
important future research efforts that augment the ideas here are listed =

below.<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
justify"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; mso-bidi-font-size: =
10.0pt"><U7:P></U7:P>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"mso-tab-count: =
1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN>System flowcharts alone do not suffice in support of business=20
process&nbsp;<SPAN style=3D"mso-bidi-font-style: =
italic">management</SPAN>.We need=20
to integrate modeling techniques like workflow management, data flow =
diagrams,=20
and others discussed in Harrington (1991).<U7:P></U7:P></SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3=20
style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; tab-stops: list .5in; mso-list: l0 level1 =
lfo2"><![if !supportLists]>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><![endif]>Object-oriented technology enables a dual role for the =
REA=20
framework as both a design paradigm and an operational framework.The REA =

approach to business process modeling should be further integrated with =
the=20
object-paradigm and most specifically with the full array of =
specification tools=20
available within UMLJacobson et al. (2000). <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3=20
style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; tab-stops: list .5in; mso-list: l0 level1 =
lfo2"><U7:P></U7:P><![if !supportLists]>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><![endif]>The Event-Task dichotomy introduced here needs to be =
analyzed=20
and extended in the directions suggested by David (1997).There will =
certainly be=20
cases where full-REA models will need to be compromised at the =
representation=20
level to show stand-alone business events (without dualities and =
resource=20
outflows for example), and heuristics for their specification need to =
developed=20
further. <o:p></o:p></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3=20
style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; tab-stops: list .5in; mso-list: l0 level1 =
lfo2"><U7:P></U7:P><![if !supportLists]>-<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><![endif]>The REA templates used here need to be extended for =
business=20
process analysis with the additional ontological primitives suggested by =
Geerts=20
and McCarthy (2000a, 2001) such as commitments and types.Use of these =
extended=20
REA patterns might possibly move process delineation of tasks and events =
from=20
more of an art guided by the heuristics given here in section 3.2 to a =
science=20
governed by basic microeconomic definitions. </P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><BR><U7:P></U7:P><U7:P></U7:P>&nbsp; </P>
